19 SECTION 45. ORS 458.670 is amended to read:
20 458.670. As used in this section and ORS 458.675 to 458.700, unless the context requires other-
21 wise:
22 (1) “Account holder” means a resident of this state who:
23 (a) Is 12 years of age or older;
24 (b) Is a member of a lower income household; and
25 (c) Has established an individual development account with a fiduciary organization.
26 (2) “Fiduciary organization” means an organization selected under ORS 458.695 to administer
27 state moneys directed to individual development accounts and that is:
28 (a) A nonprofit, fund raising organization that is exempt from taxation under section 501(c)(3)
29 of the Internal Revenue Code as amended and in effect on December 31, [2023] 2025; or
30 (b) A federally recognized Oregon Indian tribe that is located, to a significant degree, within the
31 boundaries of this state.
32 (3) “Financial institution” means:
33 (a) An organization regulated under ORS chapters 706 to 716 or 723; or
34 (b) In the case of individual development accounts established for the purpose described in ORS
35 458.685 (1)(c), a financial institution as defined in ORS 178.300.
36 (4) “Individual development account” means a contract between an account holder and a
37 fiduciary organization, for the deposit of funds into a financial institution by the account holder and
38 the deposit of matching funds into a designated account by the fiduciary organization, to allow the
39 account holder to accumulate assets for use toward achieving a specific purpose approved by the
40 fiduciary organization.
41 (5) “Lower income household” means a household having an income equal to or less than the
42 greater of the following:
43 (a) 80 percent of the median household income for the area as determined by the Housing and
44 Community Services Department. In making the determination, the department shall give consider-
45 ation to any data on area household income published by the United States Department of Housing
[44]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 and Urban Development.
2 (b) 200 percent of the poverty guidelines as determined by the Housing and Community Services
3 Department. In making the determination, the department shall give consideration to poverty
4 guidelines published by the United States Department of Health and Human Services and may con-
5 sider other income data periodically published by other federal or Oregon agencies.
6 (6)(a) “Net worth” means a calculation based on the net value of assets of a household estab-
7 lished by rule by the Housing and Community Services Department.
8 (b) “Net worth” does not include:
9 (A) Equity in one residence and in one vehicle.
10 (B) Holdings in pension accounts valued at less than $120,000.
11 (7) “Resident of this state” has the meaning given that term in ORS 316.027.
12 SECTION 46. ORS 657.010 is amended to read:
13 657.010. As used in this chapter, unless the context requires otherwise:
14 (1) “Base year” means the first four of the last five completed calendar quarters preceding the
15 benefit year.
16 (2) “Benefits” means the money allowances payable to unemployed persons under this chapter.
17 (3) “Benefit year” means a period of 52 consecutive weeks commencing with the first week with
18 respect to which an individual files an initial valid claim for benefits, and thereafter the 52 consec-
19 utive weeks period beginning with the first week with respect to which the individual next files an
20 initial valid claim after the termination of the individual’s last preceding benefit year except that
21 the benefit year shall be 53 weeks if the filing of an initial valid claim would result in overlapping
22 any quarter of the base year of a previously filed initial valid claim.
23 (4) “Calendar quarter” means the period of three consecutive calendar months ending on March
24 31, June 30, September 30 or December 31, or the approximate equivalent thereof, as the Director
25 of the Employment Department may, by rule, prescribe.
26 (5) “Client employer” means an employer that enters into a PEO relationship.
27 (6) “Client worker” means an individual who performs services for compensation for the client
28 of a professional employer organization.
29 (7) “Contribution” or “contributions” means the money payments required by this chapter, or
30 voluntary payments permitted, to be made to the Unemployment Compensation Trust Fund.
31 (8) “Covered employee” means a client worker for whom a PEO has assumed employer respon-
32 sibilities under a PEO relationship.
33 (9) “Educational institution,” including an institution of higher education, means an institution:
34 (a) In which participants, trainees or students are offered an organized course of study or
35 training designed to transfer to them knowledge, skills, information, doctrines, attitudes or abilities
36 from, by or under the guidance of an instructor or teacher;
37 (b) That is accredited, registered, approved, licensed or issued a permit to operate as a school
38 by the Department of Education or other government agency, or that offers courses for credit that
39 are transferable to an approved, registered or accredited school;
40 (c) In which the course or courses of study or training that it offers may be academic, technical,
41 trade or preparation for gainful employment in a recognized occupation; and
42 (d) In which the course or courses of study or training are offered on a regular and continuing
43 basis.
44 (10) “Employment office” means a free public employment office or branch thereof, operated by
45 this state or maintained as a part of a state-controlled system of public employment offices.
[45]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 (11) “Hospital” has the meaning given that term in ORS 442.015.
2 (12) “Institution of higher education” means an educational institution that:
3 (a) Admits as regular students only individuals having a certificate of graduation from a high
4 school, or the recognized equivalent of such a certificate;
5 (b) Is legally authorized in this state to provide a program of education beyond high school;
6 (c) Provides an educational program for which it awards a bachelor’s or higher degree, or pro-
7 vides a program that is acceptable for full credit toward such a degree, a program of post-graduate
8 or post-doctoral studies, or a program of training to prepare students for gainful employment in a
9 recognized occupation; and
10 (d) Is a public or other nonprofit institution.
11 (13) “Instructional capacity” does not include services performed as an instructional assistant
12 as defined in ORS 342.120.
13 (14) “Internal Revenue Code” means the federal Internal Revenue Code, as amended and in ef-
14 fect on December 31, [2023] 2025.
15 (15) “Labor dispute” means any concerted or deliberate action by two or more individuals or
16 by an employing unit resulting in either a strike or lockout in which wages, hours, working condi-
17 tions or terms of employment of the individuals are involved.
18 (16) “Lockout” means any refusal by an employer to permit employees to work as a result of a
19 dispute with the employees affecting wages, hours or other terms or conditions of their employment.
20 (17) “Nonprofit employing unit” means an organization, or group of organizations, described in
21 section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code that is exempt from income tax under section 501(a)
22 of the Internal Revenue Code.
23 (18) “PEO relationship” means an agreement between a PEO and a client employer under which
24 certain employer responsibilities for some or all of the client employer’s workers are allocated.
25 (19)(a) “Professional employer organization” or “PEO” means a person required to be licensed
26 under ORS 656.855 that enters into a PEO relationship with a client employer.
27 (b) “Professional employer organization” or “PEO” does not mean a person that solely provides
28 workers to a client on a temporary basis or a person that provides payroll processing or similar
29 administrative services without assuming employer responsibilities for client workers.
30 (20) “State” includes, in addition to the states of the United States of America, the District of
31 Columbia and Puerto Rico. However, for all purposes of this chapter the Virgin Islands shall be
32 considered a state on and after the day on which the United States Secretary of Labor first approves
33 the Virgin Islands’ law under section 3304(a) of the Federal Unemployment Tax Act as amended by
34 Public Law 94-566.
35 (21) “Strike” means any concerted act of employees in a lawful refusal under applicable state
36 or federal law to perform work or services for an employer.
37 (22) “Taxes” means contributions.
38 (23) “Temporary basis” means providing workers to a client:
39 (a) For special situations, including but not limited to employee absences, employee leaves,
40 professional skill shortages, seasonal workloads and special assignments and projects with the ex-
41 pectation that the position will be terminated when the special situation ends.
42 (b) As probationary new hires with a reasonable expectation of transitioning to permanent em-
43 ployment with the client, if the client uses a preestablished probationary period in its overall em-
44 ployment selection program.
45 (24) “Valid claim” means any claim for benefits made in accordance with ORS 657.260 if the
[46]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 individual meets the wages-paid-for-employment requirements of ORS 657.150.
2 (25) “Week” means any period of seven consecutive calendar days ending at midnight, as the
3 director may prescribe by rule.
4 SECTION 47. ORS 657B.010 is amended to read:
5 657B.010. As used in this chapter:
6 (1) “Alternate base year” means the last four completed calendar quarters preceding the benefit
7 year.
8 (2) “Average weekly wage” means the amount calculated by the Employment Department as the
9 state average weekly covered wage under ORS 657.150 (4)(e) as determined not more than once per
10 year.
11 (3) “Base year” means the first four of the last five completed calendar quarters preceding the
12 benefit year.
13 (4) “Benefits” means family and medical leave insurance benefits.
14 (5)(a) “Benefit year” means, except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, a period of
15 52 consecutive weeks beginning on the Sunday immediately preceding the date on which family
16 leave, medical leave or safe leave commences.
17 (b) “Benefit year” means, in the event that the 52-week period described in paragraph (a) of this
18 subsection would result in an overlap of any quarter of the base year of a previously filed valid
19 claim, a period of 53 consecutive weeks beginning on the Sunday immediately preceding the date
20 on which family leave, medical leave or safe leave commences.
21 (6) “Child” means:
22 (a) A biological child, adopted child, stepchild or foster child of a covered individual or of the
23 covered individual’s spouse or domestic partner;
24 (b) A person who is or was a legal ward of a covered individual or of the covered individual’s
25 spouse or domestic partner; or
26 (c) A person who is or was in a relationship of in loco parentis with a covered individual or
27 with the covered individual’s spouse or domestic partner.
28 (7) “Claimant” means an individual who has submitted an application or established a claim for
29 benefits.
30 (8) “Contribution” or “contributions” means the money payments made by any of the following
31 under ORS 657B.150:
32 (a) An employer;
33 (b) An employee;
34 (c) A self-employed individual;
35 (d) A tribal government; or
36 (e) An employee of a tribal government.
37 (9) “Covered individual” means any one of the following who qualifies under ORS 657B.015 to
38 receive family and medical leave insurance benefits:
39 (a) An eligible employee;
40 (b) A self-employed individual; or
41 (c) An employee of a tribal government.
42 (10) “Domestic partner” means an individual joined in a domestic partnership.
43 (11) “Domestic partnership” has the meaning given that term in ORS 106.310.
44 (12) “Eligible employee” means:
45 (a)(A) An employee who has earned at least $1,000 in wages during the base year; or
[47]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 (B) If an employee has not earned at least $1,000 in wages during the base year, an employee
2 who has earned at least $1,000 in wages during the alternate base year; and
3 (b) An employee to whom paid family and medical leave insurance benefits may be available
4 under ORS 657B.015.
5 (13) “Eligible employee’s average weekly wage” means an amount calculated by the Director of
6 the Employment Department by dividing the total wages earned by an eligible employee during the
7 base year by the number of weeks in the base year.
8 (14)(a) “Employee” means:
9 (A) An individual performing services for an employer for remuneration or under any contract
10 of hire, written or oral, express or implied.
11 (B) A home care worker as defined in ORS 410.600.
12 (b) “Employee” does not include:
13 (A) An independent contractor as defined in ORS 670.600.
14 (B) A participant in a work training program administered under a state or federal assistance
15 program.
16 (C) A participant in a work-study program that provides students in secondary or postsecondary
17 educational institutions with employment opportunities for financial assistance or vocational train-
18 ing.
19 (D) A railroad worker exempted under the federal Railroad Unemployment Insurance Act.
20 (E) A volunteer.
21 (F) A judge as defined in ORS 260.005.
22 (G) A member of the Legislative Assembly.
23 (H) A holder of public office as defined in ORS 260.005.
24 (15)(a) “Employer” means any person that employs one or more employees working anywhere in
25 this state or any agent or employee of such person to whom the duties of the person under this
26 chapter have been delegated.
27 (b) “Employer” includes:
28 (A) A political subdivision of this state or any county, city, district, authority or public corpo-
29 ration, or any instrumentality of a county, city, district, authority or public corporation, organized
30 and existing under law or charter;
31 (B) An individual;
32 (C) Any type of organization, corporation, partnership, limited liability company, association,
33 trust, estate, joint stock company or insurance company;
34 (D) Any successor in interest to an entity described in subparagraph (C) of this paragraph;
35 (E) A trustee, trustee in bankruptcy or receiver; or
36 (F) A trustee or legal representative of a deceased person.
37 (c) “Employer” does not include the federal government or a tribal government.
38 (16) “Employment agency” has the meaning given that term in ORS 658.005.
39 (17) “Family and medical leave insurance benefits” means the wage replacement benefits that
40 are available to a covered individual under ORS 657B.050 or under the terms of an employer plan
41 approved under ORS 657B.210, for family leave, medical leave or safe leave.
42 (18)(a) “Family leave” means leave from work taken by a covered individual:
43 (A) To care for and bond with a child during the first year after the child’s birth or during the
44 first year after the placement of the child through foster care or adoption;
45 (B) To effectuate the legal process required for placement of a foster child or the adoption of
[48]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 a child; or
2 (C) To care for a family member with a serious health condition.
3 (b) “Family leave” does not mean:
4 (A) Leave described in ORS 659A.159 (1)(a) except for leave to care for a child who requires
5 home care due to an illness, injury or condition that is a serious health condition;
6 (B) Leave described in ORS 659A.159 (1)(b); or
7 (C) Leave authorized under ORS 659A.093.
8 (19) “Family member” means:
9 (a) The spouse of a covered individual;
10 (b) A child or the child’s spouse or domestic partner;
11 (c) A parent or the parent’s spouse or domestic partner;
12 (d) A sibling or stepsibling of a covered individual or the sibling’s or stepsibling’s spouse or
13 domestic partner;
14 (e) A grandparent of a covered individual or the grandparent’s spouse or domestic partner;
15 (f) A grandchild of a covered individual or the grandchild’s spouse or domestic partner;
16 (g) The domestic partner of a covered individual; or
17 (h) Any individual related by blood or affinity whose close association with a covered individual
18 is the equivalent of a family relationship.
19 (20) “Medical leave” means leave from work taken by a covered individual that is made neces-
20 sary by the individual’s own serious health condition.
21 (21) “Parent” means:
22 (a) A biological parent, adoptive parent, stepparent or foster parent of a covered individual;
23 (b) A person who was a foster parent of a covered individual when the covered individual was
24 a minor;
25 (c) A person designated as the legal guardian of a covered individual at the time the covered
26 individual was a minor or required a legal guardian;
27 (d) A person with whom a covered individual was or is in a relationship of in loco parentis; or
28 (e) A parent of a covered individual’s spouse or domestic partner who meets a description under
29 paragraphs (a) to (d) of this subsection.
30 (22) “Safe leave” means leave taken for any purpose described in ORS 659A.272.
31 (23) “Self-employed individual” means:
32 (a) An individual who has self-employment income as defined in section 1402(b) of the Internal
33 Revenue Code as amended and in effect on December 31, [2023] 2025; or
34 (b) An independent contractor as defined in ORS 670.600.
35 (24) “Serious health condition” means:
36 (a) An illness, injury, impairment or physical or mental condition that requires inpatient care
37 in a hospital, hospice or residential medical care facility;
38 (b) An illness, disease or condition that in the medical judgment of the treating health care
39 provider poses an imminent danger of death, is terminal in prognosis with a reasonable possibility
40 of death in the near future, or requires constant care;
41 (c) Any period of disability due to pregnancy, or period of absence for prenatal care; or
42 (d) Any period of absence for the donation of a body part, organ or tissue, including preoperative
43 or diagnostic services, surgery, post-operative treatment and recovery.
44 (25) “Third party administrator” means a third party that enters into an agreement with the
45 Director of the Employment Department to implement and administer the paid family and medical
[49]

A-Eng. SB 1507
1 leave program established under this chapter.
2 (26) “Tribal government” means:
3 (a) A tribal government as defined in ORS 181A.940; or
4 (b) A federally recognized Indian tribe.
5 (27)(a) “Wages” has the meaning given that term in ORS 657.105.
6 (b) “Wages” does not mean contribution amounts paid to the Paid Family and Medical Leave
7 Insurance Fund by an employer on behalf of an employee under ORS 657B.150 (5).
8 SECTION 48. (1) Except as provided in subsections (2) and (3) of this section, the
9 amendments to statutes by sections 16 to 47 of this 2026 Act apply to transactions or activ-
10 ities occurring on or after January 1, 2026, in tax years beginning on or after January 1, 2026.
11 (2) The effective and applicable dates, and the exceptions, special rules and coordination
12 with the Internal Revenue Code, as amended, relative to those dates, contained in federal law
13 amending the Internal Revenue Code and enacted before January 1, 2026, apply for Oregon
14 personal income and corporate excise and income tax purposes, to the extent they can be
15 made applicable, in the same manner as they are applied under the Internal Revenue Code
16 and related federal law.
17 (3)(a) If a deficiency is assessed against any taxpayer for a tax year beginning before
18 January 1, 2026, and the deficiency or any portion thereof is attributable to any retroactive
19 treatment under the amendments to ORS 178.300, 178.375, 305.239, 305.494, 305.690, 305.842,
20 314.011, 314.306, 315.004, 316.012, 316.147, 316.157, 317.010, 317.097 and 317A.100 by sections 16,
21 17 and 31 to 44 of this 2026 Act, then any interest or penalty assessed under ORS chapter 305,
22 314, 315, 316, 317, 317A or 318 with respect to the deficiency or portion thereof shall be can-
23 celed.
24 (b) If a refund is due any taxpayer for a tax year beginning before January 1, 2026, and
25 the refund or any portion thereof is due the taxpayer on account of any retroactive treat-
26 ment under the amendments to ORS 178.300, 178.375, 305.239, 305.494, 305.690, 305.842, 314.011,
27 314.306, 315.004, 316.012, 316.147, 316.157, 317.010, 317.097 and 317A.100 by sections 16, 17 and
28 31 to 44 of this 2026 Act for a tax year beginning before January 1, 2026, then notwithstanding
29 ORS 305.270 or 314.415 or any other law, the refund or portion thereof shall be paid without
30 interest.
31 (c) Any changes required because of the amendments to ORS 178.300, 178.375, 305.239,
32 305.494, 305.690, 305.842, 314.011, 314.306, 315.004, 316.012, 316.147, 316.157, 317.010, 317.097 and
33 317A.100 by sections 16, 17 and 31 to 44 of this 2026 Act for a tax year beginning before Jan-
34 uary 1, 2026, shall be made by filing an amended return within the time prescribed by law.
35 (d) If a taxpayer fails to file an amended return under paragraph (c) of this subsection,
36 the Department of Revenue shall make any changes under paragraph (c) of this subsection
37 on the return to which the changes relate within the period specified for issuing a notice of
38 deficiency or claiming a refund as otherwise provided by law with respect to that return, or
39 within one year after a return for a tax year beginning on or after January 1, 2026, and be-
40 fore January 1, 2027, is filed, whichever period expires later.
41 SECTION 49. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
42 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
